            <div id="content">

                <h1>Using Jekyll to create websites</h1>
<p class="meta">
    Published at 07-06-2009 &bull;
    Tagged blog, blogging, jekyll, code, ruby, writing<br>
    Next: <a href="/blog/rake-task-to-ping-google.html">Rake task to ping Google</a>
    Previous: <a href="/blog/hello-world.html">Hello, world!</a>
</p>

<p class="leader">To both speed up and simplify this site‚Äôs maintenance I‚Äôve gotten rid of
traditional <abbr title="Content Management Systems">CMS</abbr>; I now use Jekyll: a static site generator. You should give it
a try if you‚Äôre not afraid of a little hacking.</p>

<h2 id="about-jekyll">About Jekyll</h2>

<p>Jekyll generates static <abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr> pages for you. The project‚Äôs author, Tom
Preston-Werner, has written <a href="http://tom.preston-werner.com/2008/11/17/blogging-like-a-hacker.html" title="Read more about Jekyll on Tom Preston-Werner's site">a nice introduction to Jekyll</a>, but it comes
down to this:</p>

<ul>
<li>Create some text files that will be your pages and blog posts.</li>
  <li>Create an <abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr> lay-out file that defines headers and footers for your pages.</li>
  <li>Run Jekyll to combine your text files and lay-out to a website.</li>
  <li>Upload your files to your server for the world to see.</li>
</ul><p>If it sounds easy, that‚Äôs because it is. I can use <a href="http://macromates.com" title="TextMate">my favourite text editor</a>
and <a href="http://git-scm.com" title="Git - Fast Version Control System">version control system</a> to write my posts, and then I let Jekyll use
<a href="http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/" title="Daring Fireball: Markdown">Markdown</a> to turn my files into <abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr>. You can also use other filters, or
write plain <abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr>.</p>

<p>Let me stress my point: I can use my favorite text editor and versioning
system for my blog, rather than some wimpy <code>&lt;textarea&gt;</code>.</p>

<h2 id="here-comes-trouble">Here comes trouble</h2>

<p>Jekyll doesn‚Äôt do a lot, by design. Some manual labour is involved, which is
to be automated ‚Äì because we don‚Äôt like manual labour, now do we? I‚Äôve
written about some of my scripts to enhance Jekyll in separate posts:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="/code/jekyll/2009/06/16/creating-new-jekyll-posts.html" title="Creating new empty posts with a rake task">Creating new posts</a></li>
  <li><a href="/code/jekyll/2009/06/13/publishing-a-jekyll-website-to-a-server.html" title="Using rsync to copy files to my server">Publishing files to a server</a></li>
  <li><a href="/code/jekyll/2009/06/10/rake-task-to-ping-google.html" title="Pinging Google with a Rake task">Ping Google about my updated sitemap</a></li>
</ul><h2 id="publication-process">Publication process</h2>

<p>I have included all these snippets, and some others, in one big Rakefile in my
project directory. Whenever I am ready to publish my site to my server I can
simply call <code>rake publish</code> and it will let Jekyll re-generate my site, upload
all the files to the server and ping Google about my new sitemap.</p>

<p>The actual <a href="http://github.com/avdgaag/arjanvandergaag.nl/tree/master" title="Browse the source code to this site at Github">source code to my site is shared publicly at Github</a>, so you
can check out <a href="http://github.com/avdgaag/arjanvandergaag.nl/blob/28539bc736a05b28f2aa4ef81e4f61f3f91375a0/Rakefile" title="See my project's Rakefile">my collection of tasks</a>.</p>

<h2 id="issues-unresolved">Issues unresolved</h2>

<p>First, since my entire website is now just static <abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr> it is <strong>no longer
possible to have comments</strong> on my site, unless I would use something like
<a href="http://disqus.com/" title="DISQUS is a Javascript-based commenting system">Disqus</a>. I‚Äôm fine without comments. Second, since Jekyll is Ruby gem,
writing more Ruby to add functionality to the website is easy ‚Äì but actually
getting it in there is a little harder. <strong>Jekyll lacks a neat plug-in
solution</strong>. Luckily it‚Äôs easy to fork Jekyll on Github and hack away. Thirdly,
setting up archive pages, searching, <abbr title="Really Simple Syndication">RSS</abbr> syndication, tagging and post
browsing <strong>take some manual labour</strong>, but for now I‚Äôm fine without them.
Jekyll is certainly not suited for everyone, but for simple sites it works fine.</p>

<h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>

<p>Jekyll makes creating and maintaining websites fun, in a geeky kind of way. I
love the control it gives me. Tom Preston-Werner writes:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>The distance from my brain to my blog has shrunk, and, in the end,
I think that will make me a better author.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>I couldn‚Äôt agree more.</p>

