                <h1>Introducing Œºtil</h1>
<p class="meta">
    Published at 08-02-2010 &bull;
    Tagged javascript, library, Œºtil, jquery, dom<br>
    Next: <a href="/blog/hello-world.html">Hello, world!</a>
    Previous: <a href="/blog/creating-new-jekyll-posts.html">Creating new Jekyll posts</a>
</p>

<p>Lately in my web development work I find myself needing some simple JavaScript tools. Usually I bring out jQuery, but sometimes it just doesn‚Äôt feel right to load an entire library in order to show and hide some elements.</p>

<p>That is why I recently started developing a tiny JavaScript toolkit of my own, called Œºtil (mu-til). It‚Äôs purpose is to make basic DOM operations a little easier without taking on too much bloat. You can find the [Œºtil at Github][].</p>

<h2 id="why-a-new-library">Why a new library?</h2>

<p>There‚Äôs more than enough JavaScript libraries out there, but here‚Äôs why I wrote one:</p>

<ul>
<li>it‚Äôs a great way to learn JavaScript.</li>
  <li>it‚Äôs nice to have a pet project</li>
  <li>I wanted something specific that other libraries did not provide</li>
  <li>It‚Äôs good to really know the tools you use</li>
</ul><p>I‚Äôll still be using bigger frameworks of course, but on some cases Œºtil will suffice and I will enjoy creating a as-lean-as-possible website.</p>

<h2 id="concepts">Concepts</h2>

<p>Œºtil only does a couple of things, all of which I have stolen from the big guys:</p>

<ul>
<li>Simple element selection</li>
  <li>Adding event observers</li>
  <li>Working with class names</li>
  <li>Adding various core extensions to String and Array</li>
  <li>Extensions to quickly add features on a per project basis.</li>
  <li>a really simple build script to concatenate and minify the Œºtil core and required plugins.</li>
  <li>a packager, to quickly generate a minified library file to include in a project.</li>
</ul><p>Œºtil doesn‚Äôt do Ajax or effects. If I need that I‚Äôm much better off with jQuery. Most of the features are extensions on the core library, and it‚Äôs nice and easy to add more.</p>

<h2 id="usage">Usage</h2>

<p>Here‚Äôs a quick code sample from the project README to show off:</p>

<pre><code class="language-js"><span class="c">// on page load</span>
<span class="pd">$</span>(<span class="kw">function</span>() {

  <span class="c">// Select all links in the content leader</span>
  <span class="pd">$</span>(<span class="s"><span class="dl">'</span><span class="k">#content p.leader a</span><span class="dl">'</span></span>)

    <span class="c">// observe the click event</span>
    .addEvent(<span class="s"><span class="dl">'</span><span class="k">click</span><span class="dl">'</span></span>, <span class="kw">function</span>(e) {

      <span class="c">// stop event propagation and prevent default link behaviour</span>
      e.stop();

      <span class="c">// Set a nice background color on its parent</span>
      <span class="pd">$</span>(<span class="lv">this</span>.parentNode).setCss({ <span class="ke">background</span>: <span class="s"><span class="dl">'</span><span class="k">#ffffe1</span><span class="dl">'</span></span> });
  });
});</code></pre>

<p>And here‚Äôs using the packager from the command line to generate a minified library file of the Œºtil core and some plugins:</p>

<pre><code>$./bin/mutil hover classes
</code></pre>

<p>This will generate a <code>mutil.min.js</code> file that includes the core library and the <code>hover</code> and <code>classes</code> plugins. Easy!</p>

<h2 id="experience">Experience</h2>

<p>Writing a little library is great fun, as you get to explore practical needs, writing documentation, code optimization and crazy JavaScript quirks. I‚Äôve learned a lot from writing Œºtil, and even if I will never use it in a production environment it was time well spent.</p>

<h2 id="dive-in">Dive in</h2>

<p>You can find the code for [Œºtil at github][], along with documentation and an issue tracker. Please do fork and hack away!</p>

<p>[Œºtil at Github]: http://github.com/avdgaag/mutil</p>

